  "notes": "PROVEN. checkbox: react control subtree has {span,svg,path}, native has {} -> missing checkmark svg (defect caught). switch (small variant, the one recorded in the svelte manifest): react control has a thumb <div>, native emits a bare <button role=switch> with zero descendants -> missing thumb (defect caught). button: both render button>span, control subtrees identical -> structurally equivalent, no false alarm. ARIA-tree bonus (observed): it INCONSISTENTLY corroborates. checkbox svg surfaces as an \"image\" AX node that native lacks (ARIA happens to catch it); but the switch thumb is aria-hidden and never appears in the AX tree, so ARIA only flags switch via a missing accessible NAME, not the missing thumb. ARIA-snapshot is therefore an unreliable proxy for presentational structural defects; the DOM element-multiset diff of the control subtree is the direct, reliable signal. LIMITATION: this method is blind to visual/style defects (wrong padding, wrong color, invisible-but-present nodes); it only catches MISSING/EXTRA structural elements. Pair with computed-style (E02) and/or pixel-diff (E01) for full 1:1 fidelity. Method is deterministic (SSR + structural compare, no pixel/AA noise)."
